05838nam a22007575i 9780822377757DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19941994ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223777577 a10.1515/97808223777572doi  a(DE-B1597)553566  a(OCoLC)1226680221  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPS169.N35bN37 1994 7aLIT0040202bisacsh00aNational Identities and Post-Americanist Narratives /cDonald E. Pease. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1994] 4cÂ©1994  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Americanists00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tNational Identities, Postmodern Artifacts, and Postnational Narratives -- tNationalism, Hypercanonization, and Huckleberry Finn -- tThe Politics of Nonidentity: A Genealogy -- tAs I Lay Dying in the Machine Age -- tFailed Cultural Narratives: America in the Postwar Era and the Story of Democracy -- tResisting History: Rear Window and the Limits of the Postwar Settlement -- tQueer Nationality -- tEngendering Paranoia in Contemporary Narrative -- tTechno-euphoria and the Discourse of the American Sublime -- tOn Becoming Oneself in Frank Lentricchia -- tMelville's Typee: U.S. Imperialism at Home and Abroad -- tMass Circulation versus The Masses: Covering the Modern Magazine Scene -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNational narratives create imaginary relations within imagined communities called national peoples. But in the American narrative, alongside the nexus of belonging established for the national community, the national narrative has represented other peoples (women, blacks, "foreigners", the homeless) from whom the property of nationness has been removed altogether and upon whose differences from them the national people depended for the construction of their norms. Dismantling this opposition has become the task of post-national (Post-Americanist) narratives, bent on changing the assumptions that found the "national identity."This volume, originally published as a special issue of bounrary 2, focuses on the process of assembling and dismantling the American national narrative(s), sketching its inception and demolition. The contributors examine various cultural, political, and historical sources--colonial literature, mass movements, epidemics of disease, mass spectacle, transnational corporations, super-weapons, popular magazines, literary texts--out of which this narrative was constructed, and propose different understandings of nationality and identity following in its wake.Contributors. Jonathan Arac, Lauren Berlant, Robert J. Corber, Elizabeth Freeman, Kathryn V. Lingberg, Jack Matthews, Alan Nadel, Patrick O'Donnell, Daniel O'Hara, Donald E. Pease, Ross Posnock, John Carlos Rowe, Rob Wilson  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aAmerican literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aMinorities in literature. 0aMinorities in motion pictures. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aNarration (Rhetoric). 0aNational characteristics, American, in literature. 0aNational characteristics, American, in motion pictures. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aNadel, Alan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO'Hara, Daniel T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPease, Donald E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFreeman, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRowe, John Carlos, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatthews, John T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArac, Jonathan, econt